---
layout: layouts/service-subpage.njk
title: "Federal Employee Benefits Planning | Capital Wealth"
description: "Specialized retirement planning for federal employees. FERS optimization, TSP management, FEGLI analysis, FEHB coordination, and more. Lehi, Utah."
serviceTag: "federal"
breadcrumbs:
  - { name: "Home", url: "/" }
  - { name: "Services", url: "/services/" }
  - { name: "Federal Employee Benefits", url: "/services/federal-benefits/" }
faqSchema:
  - question: "Should I roll over my TSP when I retire?"
    answer: "It depends on your situation. TSP has very low fees and solid fund options (especially the G Fund). However, an IRA rollover gives you more investment flexibility, Roth conversion opportunities, and simplified beneficiary planning. We analyze both options and recommend what's best for your specific situation."
  - question: "Is FEGLI worth keeping into retirement?"
    answer: "Rarely. FEGLI costs increase dramatically after retirement, and most federal retirees can get better coverage at lower cost through private insurance. We analyze your coverage needs and compare FEGLI's post-retirement costs against private alternatives — many clients save thousands per year."
  - question: "How do I coordinate FEHB with Medicare?"
    answer: "If you keep FEHB into retirement (which you should), it coordinates with Medicare as your primary coverage. Medicare becomes your primary insurance, and FEHB acts as secondary, often covering your Medicare out-of-pocket costs. This combination provides excellent coverage at a reasonable cost."
  - question: "When is the best time to retire as a federal employee?"
    answer: "The optimal retirement date depends on your MRA (Minimum Retirement Age), years of service, and financial situation. You need 30 years for an unreduced pension at MRA, or age 60 with 20 years, or age 62 with 5 years. We model different retirement dates to show you the financial impact of retiring early versus waiting."
  - question: "How much should I have saved in TSP before I retire?"
    answer: "There's no one-size-fits-all number. Your TSP needs depend on your FERS pension amount, Social Security, retirement lifestyle, and other income sources. We create detailed projections showing exactly how much TSP you need based on your specific situation."
---

